";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:20:"http://www.cato.org/";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:1;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";s:5:"child";a:3:{s:0:"";a:6:{s:5:"title";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:57:"No Labels Is No real Alternative to Conventional Politics";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:20:"http://www.cato.org/";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:1;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:4:"link";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:110:"http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/CatoDispatch/~3/rmsix21dU1Q/no-labels-no-real-alternative-conventional-politics";s:7:"attribs";a:0:{}s:8:"xml_base";s:20:"http://www.cato.org/";s:17:"xml_base_explicit";b:1;s:8:"xml_lang";s:0:"";}}s:11:"description";a:1:{i:0;a:5:{s:4:"data";s:8376:"<p>Gene Healy</p>


<p>In his State of the Union address last week, President Obama demanded &ldquo;a year of action.&rdquo;</p>
<p>But what we really need, Reps. Ami Bera, D-Calif., and Chris Gibson, R-N.Y., suggested in their <a target="_blank" href="http://www.realclearpolitics.com/video/2014/01/29/reps_chris_gibson_r-ny_and_ami_bera_d-ca_deliver_no_labels_sotu_response.html">SOTU response</a> for the post-partisan, good-government group No Labels, is &ldquo;a government of collaboration.&rdquo; Not in the Vichyite sense, don&#8217;t worry&mdash;what No Labels proposes is a government with a &ldquo;formula for how to get our leaders in Washington to start solving problems together again.&rdquo;</p>
<blockquote class="pullquote right">
 <p class="pq-quote"><span class="open-quote">&ldquo;</span><span class="pq-body">It&#8217;s easy to make fun of No Labels; but it&#8217;s also important, because their empty pieties offer no real alternative to business as usual.&rdquo;</span></p>
</blockquote>
<p>What that &ldquo;formula&rdquo; might be is never quite clear, but it starts with our representatives moving their flag pins to make room for new congressional &ldquo;flair.&rdquo; Over 70 members showed up to the SOTU sporting NL&#8217;s orange &ldquo;Problem Solvers&rdquo; pin. The standard, grammatically-challenged version says &ldquo;Committed to Fix Not Fight,&rdquo; but, for a night on the town, congressmen can download <a target="_blank" href="http://www.nolabels.org/choose-download-your-pin">sexier alternatives</a>, like &ldquo;Make Love, Not Gridlock&rdquo; or &ldquo;No More No.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Launched in 2010 to &ldquo;move America from the old politics of point-scoring toward a new politics of problem-solving,&rdquo; No Labels is back, with a &ldquo;three-year campaign to create a national strategic agenda&rdquo; and a new book, <em>No Labels: A Shared Vision for a Stronger America.</em></p>
<p>&ldquo;The grownups show up,&rdquo; gushes <a target="_blank" href="http://www.amazon.com/review/R1H8RC7EYRZJJ8">one Amazon reviewer.</a> But if these are the &ldquo;grownups,&rdquo; why do they come wearing happy-face buttons and spouting get-along bromides that might have been drawn from a middle-school &ldquo;No Putdowns&rdquo; campaign? Does Congress really need its own anti-bullying movement?</p>
<p>In the book&rsquo;s introduction, No Labels co-chairman Jon Huntsman laments the partisan state of the State of the Union: &ldquo;If we had a national strategic agenda this could all be different. The president and the leader of the opposition could meet before the State of the Union&rdquo; and &ldquo;get agreement on goals before the policy-making process starts.&rdquo;</p>
<p>This is how &ldquo;grownups&rdquo; are supposed to think about politics? When the old <em>New York Sun</em> started calling &ldquo;good government&rdquo; reformers &ldquo;goo-goos&rdquo; in the 1890s, they didn&#8217;t know the half of it.</p>
<p>NL&rsquo;s &ldquo;Problem-Solvers&rdquo; blog features a Rubik&rsquo;s Cube logo; as long as we&rsquo;re living in the &lsquo;80s, &ldquo;where&rsquo;s the beef?&rdquo; is a relevant question. What is this &ldquo;national strategic agenda&rdquo; anyway?</p>
<p>It involves agreement on &ldquo;four essential goals&rdquo;: 1. 25 million new jobs; 2. Medicare and Social Security solvency; 3. balancing the budget; and 4. making America &ldquo;energy self-sufficient.&rdquo;</p>
<p>The last item is mercantilist nonsense, but all four goals are already widely shared by pols. If we haven&#8217;t achieved them, &ldquo;it&#8217;s not because the solutions aren&#8217;t clear,&rdquo; No Labels argues, &ldquo;but because we haven&#8217;t focused our talents and resources.&rdquo; &ldquo;No one ever actually tells us how they plan&rdquo; to unite America, co-chairman Sen. Joe Manchin, D-W.Va., writes in the book&#8217;s foreword, &ldquo;in the pages ahead, you&#8217;ll read about the ?how.’&rdquo; Many platitudinous pixels later, the authors write that &ldquo;there will be a lot of tough decisions ahead. &#8230; in this book, however, we have purposely stopped short of suggesting which tradeoffs will be needed.&rdquo; I see.</p>
<p>It&rsquo;s easy to make fun of No Labels; but it&rsquo;s also important, because their empty pieties offer no real alternative to business as usual.</p>
<p>Meanwhile, some of Congress&#8217;s archest ideologues have proven themselves capable of cross-aisle cooperation on important issues like National Security Agency reform. Socialist Bernie Sanders of Vermont and libertarian Justin Amash, R-Mich., have joined to tackle the problem of the surveillance state without the benefit of a &ldquo;Problem Solvers&rdquo; pin&mdash;as have Rep. James Sensenbrenner, R-Ill., and Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt., cosponsors of the <a target="_blank" href="http://sensenbrenner.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=356911">USA Freedom Act</a>.</p>
<p>Solving that problem will take a fight, but there&#8217;s no &ldquo;fixing&rdquo; without &ldquo;fighting.&rdquo;</p>


