<p>My fellow Americans, the State of the Union is &#8230; irrelevant.</p>
<p>Quick: Give me a memorable line from any of President Obama&#8217;s previous five SOTUs. That&#8217;s what I thought. I couldn&#8217;t give you one offhand &mdash; and it&#8217;s my job to watch these pompous, unedifying spectacles and <a href="http://www.cato.org/publications/commentary/problem-state-union-isnt-seating">write about them</a>.</p>
<blockquote class="pullquote right">
 <p class="pq-quote"><span class="open-quote">&ldquo;</span><span class="pq-body">In its modern form, the SOTU is a meaningless ritual that rarely even does the president &mdash; let alone the public &mdash; any good.&rdquo;</span></p>
</blockquote>
<p>The few enduring lines from past SOTUs stick out for irony value (Bill Clinton in 1996: &ldquo;the era of big government is over&rdquo;); because they herald a looming policy disaster (George W. Bush in 2002: &ldquo;Axis of Evil&rdquo;) &mdash; or for the rare outbreak of candor (Gerald Ford in 1975: &ldquo;the state of the union is not good&rdquo;).</p>
<p>But most years, the speech gets submerged in the churn of the news cycle, little noted and not long remembered. It&rsquo;s unlikely that 2014 will be any different. In its modern form, the SOTU is a meaningless ritual that rarely even does the president &mdash; let alone the public &mdash; any good.</p>
<p>That&#8217;s bad news for a chief executive whose chief talent is speechifying. &ldquo;I have a gift, Harry,&rdquo; then-Sen. Obama unhumble bragged to Sen. Harry Reid, D-Nev., some years ago, in the afterglow of a well-received speech. But according to the polling data and the political science research, it&#8217;s a gift that won&#8217;t keep on giving.</p>
<p>&ldquo;There is overwhelming evidence that presidents, even great communicators,’ rarely move the public in their direction,&rdquo; <a target="_blank" href="http://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2357130">writes George C. Edwards III,</a> a presidential scholar at Texas A&amp;M University. &ldquo;Going public does not work.&rdquo; In a 2013 analysis of SOTU polling, <a target="_blank" href="http://papers.ssrn.com/sol3/papers.cfm?abstract_id=2357130">Gallup found that</a>&ldquo; most presidents have shown an average <em>decrease</em> in approval of one or more points between the last poll conducted before the State of the Union and the first one conducted afterward.&rdquo;</p>
<p>As the speech has become less important, presidents&rsquo; rhetoric has grown more frantically stentorian. Presidential scholar Elvin T. Lim notes &ldquo;increasing rhetorical assertiveness&rdquo; and &ldquo;an increasing lack of humility&rdquo; in the language of the SOTU over time. Modern presidents speak more often of &ldquo;reform,&rdquo; while &ldquo;references to (and hence concern for) the Constitution and constitutional in the annual messages have declined.&rdquo;</p>
<p>You&rsquo;d hardly imagine it from watching the speech, but the SOTU has constitutional roots, in the duty imposed on the president by Article II, sec. 3: &ldquo;he shall from time to time give to the Congress Information of the State of the Union and recommend to their Consideration such Measures as he shall judge necessary and expedient.&rdquo;</p>
<p>Modern presidents do a lot more hectoring than recommending, treating the SOTU as an occasion to tell Congress what to do. That doesn&#8217;t mean Congress actually does it: The speech is &ldquo;high volume, low yield&rdquo; in terms of legislative success, as a recent Associated Press analysis puts it.</p>
<p>Which, no doubt, is why the administration is signaling that tonight&#8217;s SOTU will be less about telling Congress what to do than it is about telling them what he plans to do without them. This will be &ldquo;a year of action,&rdquo; White House press secretary Jay Carney said Sunday, and the president will &ldquo;bypass Congress where necessary to lift folks who want to come up into the middle class.&rdquo; The White House has hinted at unilateral action on issues like carbon emissions, student loans, and job training. &ldquo;We need to show the American people that we can get something done,&rdquo; says presidential adviser Dan Pfeiffer.</p>
<p>It seems the president plans to go it alone, loudly. But in a recent Christian Science Monitor/TIPP poll, 55 percent of Americans disapproved of presidents &ldquo;taking executive action when Congress is gridlocked.&rdquo; He&#8217;ll have to talk them into liking it.</p>


<a href="http://www.cato.org/people/gene-healy">Gene Healy</a>, a Washington Examiner columnist, is vice president at the Cato Institute and author of <a href="http://store.cato.org/books/cult-presidency-america-s-dangerous-devotion-executive-power-hardback">The Cult of the Presidency</a><em>.</em><div class="feedflare">
